<br>
Keeping the free cigarette distribution in age-restricted areas is also reasonable.  People who are going to smoke will get their cigarettes regardless of marketing.  Children will be presented with free cigarettes from their peers long before any tobacco company gets near them.  It is entirely up to the parents and schools to convince them not to smoke.<br>
<br>
I don't smoke.  I hate the smell, it makes breathing difficult when it gets too thick.  The smell will cling to clothing and make you smell like a bar, even if you were only riding in a car with a smoker.  Not to mention the huge stack of medical things that get stuck on the packs with the surgeon generals warning.<br>
<br>
I do however respect other peoples right to poison their own bodies with whatever pollutant they prefer.<br>
<br>
I also think that the cigarette companies should have the rights to the same kinds of marketing that alcohol companies have.  It is an age-restricted substance, then only distribute it to people of the right age.  Sounds to me like they were doing a better job of that than most of the free-alcohol campus events I have seen. <p><center><img src="http://cleric.homestead.com/files/mathi.jpg" border="0">
</a> </center>
